(24, 1, '2022-04-13 20:10:57', '2022-04-13 20:10:57', '<!-- wp:image {\"id\":25,\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\",\"className\":\"is-style-rounded\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-style-rounded\"><img src=\"http://localhost/blog/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/shutterstock_510365275-850x525-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-25\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bulbs are little packets of flower power that make us wait weeks, sometimes months, for results — but boy, are they worth it. The term “bulb” often refers not only to true bulbs, but also plants with tuberous roots, tubers, corms, and rhizomes; the information here can be applied to all of these. With a little basic knowledge, anyone can grow beautiful bulbs.<strong>On this page:</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li><a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/bulbs/how-to.html#types\">TYPES OF BULBS</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/bulbs/how-to.html#planting\">PLANTING BULBS</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/bulbs/how-to.html#care\">DIGGING &amp; STORING BULBS</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/bulbs/how-to.html#hints\">HELPFUL HINTS</a></li><li><a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/bulbs/how-to.html#buying\">BUYING BULBS</a></li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>TYPES OF BULBS</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Bulbs can be separated into two main types: spring and summer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Spring bulbs:</strong>&nbsp;Also called hardy bulbs, these bulbs are planted in fall, spend winter in the ground, and flower in spring. Some of the more common spring bulbs are&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/bulbs/tulips.html\">tulips</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/flowers/iris.html\">irises</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/bulbs/daffodils.html\">daffodils</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/bulbs/hyacinth.html\">hyacinth</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/bulbs/alliums.html\">allium</a>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/flowers/crocus.html\">crocus</a>. These bulbs need several weeks of cold temperatures to break their dormancy and flower to their full potential. (See more:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/bulbs/spring/html\">Spring Bulbs</a>.)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Summer bulbs:</strong>&nbsp;Also called tender bulbs, these bulbs are planted in spring and flower or leaf out in summer.&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/flowers/gladiolus.html\">Gladiolus</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/flowers/lilies.html\">lilies</a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/plants/caladium.html\">caladiums</a>, and&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/plants/elephant-ear.html\">elephant ears</a>&nbsp;are common examples of summer bulbs. Some will bloom later in summer or for a longer time, like&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/dahlias/\">dahlias</a>&nbsp;that bloom into fall. (See more:&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.gardendesign.com/bulbs/summer.html\">Summer Bulbs</a>.)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Summer bulbs aren\'t tolerant of cold temperatures and should only be planted after the ground warms up and there\'s no longer a threat of frost. If purchased before planting time, store them in a cool, dry spot until planting.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Bulbs', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'bulbs', '', '', '2022-04-13 20:10:57', '2022-04-13 20:10:57', '', 0, 'http://localhost/blog/?p=24', 0, 'post', '', 0),
